references: We use two known data sets from the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository [29], the Adult data set because it is seen as a benchmark set for k-nearest neighbours [35] and the Student Performance set. The Student Performance set has a different structure, as can be seen in Table I. We use a set with a different structure as this could help gaining insight in how far these findings extend to different kinds of data sets. However to keep as many parameters equal we modify the Student Performance set such that it will also become a binary prediction task, as seen in earlier literature [36]. Furthermore, we use the Portuguese class as this contains more instances (n=649𝑛649n=649) compared to the mathematics class (n=395𝑛395n=395).

For the creation of synthetic data we use the DataSynthesizer by Ping et al. [20], as literature suggests that this method has the lowest information loss compared to other modules [21]. To minimise randomness the parameter for differential privacy is switched off and the degree of the Bayesian network is set to 2 as in the DataSynthesizer examples [20]. The number of instances that will be created is set to the length of the data set as shown in Table I. As with k𝑘k-anonymity we provide the hyperparameters on GitHub.

In Table II we observe that creating synthetic data requires a higher run time than anonymising to obtain k𝑘k-anonymity. In accordance with these findings we observe that the energy consumption is nearly 4 times higher for synthetic data. This is expected as the DataSynthesizer requires more steps to come to the new data than the ARX algorithm. We also find that the DataSynthesizer required more time for the Student Performance set than for the Adult data set, even though the Adult set contains more data as a whole. This might be explained by the DataSynthesizer having to analyse all features to create their respective probability distribution. Since the Student Performance set contains more attributes, as seen in Table I, we hypothesise that this leads to more required run time for the Student Performance set.

references: In Table IV we present the results of the energy consumption for the Adult data set on the left and the Student Performance set on the right. The benchmark is presented on the first row, after which the results are shown for the models trained on either anonymised or synthetic data. We present the deviation in percentages to the benchmark for these methods. The machine learning models are abbreviated to increase readability. In Figures 3 and 4 we present a scatterplot of the data points for k𝑘k-anonymity and synthetic data respectively. Complementary we provide the results of the Mann Whitney U test in Table V. Lastly, the idle energy consumption of the machine is measured. For each second of inactivity 7.512 Joules is consumed by the machine.

Finally, for the energy consumption. In general logistic regression is computationally efficient [33], which should result in a lower energy consumption. For both sets Table IV shows that logistic regression consumes the least amount of energy compared to the other machine learning methods. Contrary to this finding, k-nearest neighbours becomes computationally more complex as the size of the data grows [33]. Table IV shows that indeed for the Adult set the k-nearest neighbours algorithm used ∼similar-to\sim152 times more energy while the Adult set is just ∼similar-to\sim17 times larger than the Student Performance set, confirming this statement. The energy consumption of neural network depends on many parameters [38], which makes it hard to compare the baseline to literature.

For the energy consumption of models trained on the Adult data set, the left-side of Table IV shows us that the synthetic data lies in close range compared to the benchmark. This indicates that the DataSynthesizer has similar characteristics to the original data. For the models trained on anonymised data using k𝑘k-anonymity we see a clear deviation from the benchmark. Depending on the chosen k𝑘k-value, the run time and energy consumption decrease. Similar to other work, we find that the run time and energy consumption decrease as we increase our k𝑘k-value [22]. Additionally, Figure 3 shows that the measurements for models trained using k𝑘k-anonymity are closely clustered around their mean. This indicates that there is little variation amongst the data. We see a similar trend in Figure 4 for the models trained on synthetic data. Affirmative with these findings are the results of the Mann Whitney U test, presented in Table V. The outcomes in this table show that the probability of the higher k𝑘k-values resulting in a higher energy cost are less than 0.01. Hence we can reject this hypothesis and confirm that the higher k𝑘k-values lead to a lower energy consumption. Finally we see that the probability for synthetic data consuming more energy compared to any k𝑘k-value is >> 0.99. So we may conclude that models trained on synthetic data consume significantly more energy than the same models trained on anonymised data using k𝑘k-anonymity.

When we look at the right-side of Table IV and compare it to our findings on the Adult set, we find that the smaller Student Performance set also has a lower run time and related lower energy consumption. This finding holds for the benchmark as well as for the anonymised and synthetic data. Similar to the Adult data, we observe that the synthetic data shows close resemblance to the benchmark. This similarity extends to the anonymised data, where we see both the run time and energy consumption decrease as the chosen k𝑘k-value increases. In addition, Figures 3 and 4 clearly show that the data points are clustered with little variation around their mean. As with the Adult data set, we see in Table V that the probability of higher k𝑘k-values resulting in a higher energy cost are less than 0.01. Again the probability of models trained on synthetic data resulting in a higher energy consumption are >> 0.99.

The benchmark reflects the accuracy scores for the unmodified or original data. To reflect the accuracies as accurate as possible we present the accuracy scores instead of the deviation to the benchmark.

In this section we compare the accuracy and energy consumption of our presented benchmark in Table VI to the accuracy presented in other work. Since the goal of this paper is to examine the effect of anonymised data or synthetic data compared to original data, small differences in regard to other literature are deemed acceptable.

Literature suggests that for k-nearest neighbours and logistic regression accuracies of 71.0% and 76.0% may be expected. Table VI shows that our models deviate 1.0% and 4.1% respectively. As mentioned earlier, the focus of this paper lies on the difference between the benchmark and anonymised or synthetic data and thus we deem this difference acceptable. For the neural network, no work was found that used all columns for this task. The original paper reports an accuracy of 83.4% but that included a larger network and hyperparameters that were optimised using grid search [36].
For the accuracy of the models we divide our discussion in two parts; one component for the Adult set and another component for the Student Performance set. We study Table VI in this section.
